<h3>SYSTEMIC EXAMINATION</h3>
<div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="949" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/q3A0QIX7zt4" title="Abdominal Examination | Aspire PLAB/UKMLA Academy" width="1976"></iframe> </div>
<br/>
<p><em><b>Prerequisites for Abdominal Examination:</b> Explain procedure:
        "Anne now I'm going to examine your tummy" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=25s">Video 0:25</a>). Ensure adequate exposure: "I would
        like you to undress above your waist" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=29s">Video 0:29</a>) - (Standard is from xiphisternum to
        pubic symphysis, thighs exposed). Offer/confirm chaperone: "I have the
        shaon [chaperone] to ensure your privacy" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=31s">Video 0:31</a>). Obtain consent: "May I proceed?" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=34s">Video
          0:34</a>). Ask about pain before starting: "Do you have got pain
        anywhere" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=37s">Video 0:37</a>). Inform patient: "I'll be gentle and
        quick but at any point of time you feel uncomfortable or you want me to
        stop just let me know I'll stop my examination" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=38s">Video 0:38-0:46</a>). Patient supine.</em></p>
<p> POSITIONS : (General sequence followed in video and standard practice)</p>
<ol>
<li>INSPECTION (General &amp; Abdominal)</li>
<li>PALPATION (Superficial &amp; Deep, including specific organs)</li>
<li>PERCUSSION</li>
<li>AUSCULTATION</li>
<li>REGIONAL LYMPH NODES (e.g., supraclavicular - Virchow's node)</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>GENERAL INSPECTION (Peripheral Signs before focusing on Abdomen):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Hands:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=50s">Video 0:50-0:56</a>)
        <ul>
<li>Palmar erythema. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=56s">Video 0:56-0:58</a>)</li>
<li>Dupuytren's contracture. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=58s">Video 0:58-1:01</a>)</li>
<li>Turn over hands (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=61s">Video 1:01</a>): Nail changes (koilonychia,
            leukonychia). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=63s">Video 1:03-1:07</a>)</li>
<li>Finger clubbing (Shamroth's sign). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=67s">Video 1:07-1:17</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Arms:</strong>
<ul>
<li>Asterixis (flapping tremor): Patient extends arms and doriflexes
            wrists. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=77s">Video 1:17-1:24</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Eyes:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=90s">Video 1:30</a>)
        <ul>
<li>Conjunctival pallor (pull eyelids down, patient looks up). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=90s">Video 1:30-1:37</a>)</li>
<li>Scleral icterus (patient looks down). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=97s">Video 1:37-1:43</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Mouth:</strong> Patient opens mouth, lifts tongue. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=103s">Video 1:43-1:51</a>)
        <ul>
<li>Angular stomatitis. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=111s">Video 1:51</a>)</li>
<li>Oral candidiasis. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=111s">Video 1:51</a>)</li>
<li>Mouth ulcers. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=113s">Video 1:53</a>)</li>
<li>Glossitis. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=117s">Video 1:57</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Neck Lymph Nodes:</strong> "feel lumps and bumps in your neck"
        (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=117s">Video
          1:57-2:03</a>)
        <ul>
<li>Left supraclavicular lymph node (Virchow's node - specific for
            gastric carcinoma). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=128s">Video 2:08-2:20</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Chest:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=143s">Video 2:23</a>)
        <ul>
<li>Spider naevi. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=146s">Video 2:26</a>)</li>
<li>Gynaecomastia. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=146s">Video 2:26</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>EXAMINATION OF ABDOMEN</p>
<ol>
<li>INSPECTION (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=181s">Video 3:01</a>): From the foot end of the bed, at
        eye level.
        <ol>
<li>SHAPE: "abdomen is not distended". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=181s">Video 3:01-3:05</a>)</li>
<li>FLANKS: Fullness (e.g., in ascites).</li>
<li>DISTENSION: Uniform or localized.</li>
<li>MOVEMENT OF ABD WITH RESPIRATION: Observe. Upper abdominal viscera
            normally move.
            <ol>
<li>Liver</li>
<li>Gall bladder</li>
<li>Stomach</li>
<li>Spleen</li>
<li>Hepatic flexure</li>
<li>Splenic flexure</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ANY ENGORGED VEINS: (e.g., caput medusae).</li>
<li>UMBLICUS: "amus [umbilicus] is centrally placed and inverted". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=185s">Video
              3:05-3:09</a>)
            <ol>
<li>Inverted/flat/everted</li>
<li>Vertical/transverse slit like</li>
<li>Any herniation</li>
<li>Any discharge</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>SKIN OVER ABD: "no scar marks no stri". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=189s">Video 3:09-3:13</a>)
            <ol>
<li>Scars (location, size, healing)</li>
<li>Sinuses</li>
<li>Striae (rubra/alba)</li>
<li>Linea alba/nigra</li>
<li>Petechiae</li>
<li>Pigmentation</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>VISIBLE PULSATIONS: "no visible pulsation in the tummy". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=193s">Video 3:13-3:16</a>)
            <ol>
<li>AAA</li>
<li>Tumors over aorta</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>VISIBLE PERISTALSIS: (e.g., in intestinal obstruction, thin
            patient).</li>
<li>HERNIAL ORIFICES: (Ask patient to cough if suspected).
            <ol>
<li>INGUINAL</li>
<li>FEMORAL</li>
<li>INCISIONAL</li>
<li>UMBLICAL</li>
<li>EPIGASTRIC AREA</li>
</ol>
</li>
<!-- Items like COUGH IMPULSE / IMPULSE ON CRYING / MOVEMENT WITH DEGLUTATION / PROTRUSION OF TONGUE / PRESSURE EFFECTS LIMB DISTAL are more for discrete swellings rather than general abdominal inspection -->
</ol>
</li>
<li>PALPATION: (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=196s">Video 3:16</a>) Ask patient if they have pain
        anywhere before starting (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=199s">Video 3:19</a>). Look at patient's face for
        tenderness. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=207s">Video 3:27</a>)
        <ol>
<li>SUPERFICIAL PALPATION: For tenderness, cover all nine quadrants
            (S-shaped formation mentioned). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=204s">Video 3:24-3:40</a>)
            <ol>
<li>"no tenderness on superficial palpation". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=225s">Video 3:45-3:50</a>)</li>
<li>Surface temperature (dorsum of fingers) - not explicitly shown
                but standard.</li>
<li>Rigidity &amp; Guarding.</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>DEEP PALPATION: "press a bit deeper". Same S-shaped pattern,
            covering all nine quadrants. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=230s">Video 3:50-4m17s</a>)
            <ol>
<li>Any rebound tenderness.</li>
<li>Any localized mass.</li>
<li>Direction of flow in prominent veins (if present).</li>
<li>Divarication of recti.</li>
<li>Any pulsations (e.g., expansile for AAA). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=397s">Video 6:37-6:50 for Aorta palpation</a>)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ORGAN PALPATION:
            <ol>
<li><strong>Liver:</strong> Start from right iliac fossa, ask
                patient to take deep breaths in and out. Go in when patient
                breathes in. Try to feel border of liver. "I cannot feel the
                edge of the liver". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=261s">Video 4:21-5m0s</a>)
                <ul>
<li>Murphy's Sign (for acute cholecystitis): Press on
                    subcostal margin, patient breathes in and holds. Pain on
                    inspiration = positive. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=300s">Video 5:00-5m31s</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Spleen:</strong> Start from right iliac fossa (as
                spleen enlarges towards RIF). Patient breathes in and out, go in
                when patient breathes in. "I cannot feel spleen as well". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=331s">Video 5:31-6m10s</a>)</li>
<li><strong>Kidneys (Ballotment):</strong> One hand posteriorly,
                other anteriorly to try and palpate/ballot. Kidneys
                "non-ballotable" usually. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=370s">Video 6:10-6m37s</a>)</li>
<li><strong>Gallbladder:</strong> (Usually not palpable unless
                enlarged/diseased).</li>
<li><strong>Colon:</strong> (May feel faeces).</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ANY LUMP / MASS (if found, describe per swelling proforma - Site,
            Size, Shape, Surface, Edge, Consistency, Mobility, etc.)</li>
<li>HERNIAL ORIFICES: (Re-check if concerned).</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>PERCUSSION:
        <ol>
<li><strong>Liver Span:</strong> Percuss from resonant lung down to
            dullness (upper border), then from tympanitic abdomen up to dullness
            (lower border). Mark and measure. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=410s">Video 6:50-7m40s</a>)</li>
<li><strong>Spleen (Traube's Space):</strong> (Normally resonant).</li>
<li><strong>Shifting Dullness (for Ascites):</strong> Percuss from
            midline (tympanitic) laterally until dull. Ask patient to tilt to
            their side, wait 30 seconds, re-percuss same spot. If now tympanitic
            = dullness has shifted. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=460s">Video 7:40-8m29s</a>)</li>
<li><strong>Fluid Thrill (for major ascites/effusion):</strong>
            Patient places ulnar border of their hand firmly in midline. Tap one
            flank, feel for thrill on other flank. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=513s">Video 8:33-8m58s</a>)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>AUSCULTATION: (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=541s">Video 9:01</a>)
        <ol>
<li><strong>Bowel Sounds:</strong> "I can hear the bowel sound".
            Listen in one or more quadrants. Note character. "before we say
            absence bowel sound we have to hear at least for 2 minutes". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=550s">Video 9:10-9m20s</a>)</li>
<li><strong>Bruits:</strong> (Renal, aortic, iliac - for vascular
            pathology).</li>
<li>(Splenic rub, hepatic bruit - less common).</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><strong>COMPLETION OF EXAMINATION:</strong> "To complete the
        examination we will be checking for hernial sites and we should be doing
        digital rectal examination". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q3A0QIX7zt4&amp;t=560s">Video 9:20-9m29s</a>)
        <ul>
<li>Genital examination (if relevant to presenting complaint).</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="949" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/wlwXTnYKqmA" title="Per Rectal Examination (PR) - OSCE Guide" width="1792"></iframe> </div>
<br/>
<ol>
<li>SPECIAL TESTS
        <ul>
<li><strong>PER RECTAL EXAMINATION (DRE)</strong> </li>
<li><em>Indications from transcript:</em> Suspected Prostate Cancer,
            BPH (Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=8s">Video 0:08-0:20</a>)</li>
<li><em><b>Prerequisites &amp; Explanation to Patient:</b></em>
<ul>
<li>Explain the procedure: "I'm gonna insert my glove lubricated
                finger in your back passage." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=26s">Video 0:26-0:31</a>)</li>
<li>Patient position: "Patient should be lying down on the left
                lateral position... bring their knees towards the chest." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=31s">Video 0:31-0:43</a>)</li>
<li>Exposure: "Patient has to undress below the waist." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=46s">Video 0:46-0:49</a>)</li>
<li>Chaperone: "We have a chaperone to ensure the patient
                privacy." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=49s">Video 0:49-0:52</a>)</li>
<li>Consent must be obtained.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><em><b>Procedure Steps:</b></em>
<ol>
<li>Ensure you are gloved and have lubricant gel. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=57s">Video 0:57-1:02</a>)</li>
<li>Apply anesthetic jelly to the anus. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=73s">Video 1:13-1:17</a>)</li>
<li>Advise waiting a minute for the jelly to work and the anal
                sphincter to relax. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=77s">Video 1:17-1:30</a>)</li>
<li>Inform the patient before inserting the finger. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=90s">Video 1:30-1:34</a>)</li>
<li>Assess Anal Tone: Ask the patient to squeeze your finger. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=94s">Video
                  1:34-1:38</a>)</li>
<li>Assess for Prolapse: Ask the patient to cough. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=101s">Video 1:41-1:43</a>)</li>
<li>Systematic Palpation:
                <ul>
<li>Check all sides of the rectum. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=107s">Video 1:47-1:51</a>)</li>
<li>Palpate Prostate (anteriorly): (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=111s">Video 1:51-1:56</a>)
                    <ul>
<li>Feel for both lobes of the prostate. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=119s">Video 1:59-2:02</a>)</li>
<li>Feel for the median sulcus. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=122s">Video 2:02</a>)</li>
<li>Normal findings: Both lobes palpable, median sulcus
                        not deep. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=122s">Video 2:02-2:09</a>)</li>
<li>Abnormal findings (BPH): Enlarged lobes, median sulcus
                        very deep. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=132s">Video 2:12-2:20</a>)</li>
<li>Abnormal findings (Cancer): Surface is quite hard. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=140s">Video 2:20-2:26</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Withdrawal: Inform the patient, "I'm going to take the finger
                out." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=148s">Video 2:28-2:31</a>)</li>
<li>Inspect Gloved Finger: Look for any fecal matter or bleeding.
                (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=151s">Video 2:31-2:33</a>)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><em><b>Post-Procedure:</b></em>
<ul>
<li>Offer wipes to the patient. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=153s">Video 2:33-2:37</a>)</li>
<li>Thank the patient. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=157s">Video 2:37-2:39</a>)</li>
<li>Allow the patient to dress up. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=159s">Video 2:39-2:41</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
